Ed, I like the way you write. It gives meaning to the word &quot;warrior&quot;.  Meaning that is based in culture and folklore and history.  It gives a granduer to something I always thought as common. Truck drivers, cooks, POL operators, hq clerks are common.  The commonality is the brotherhood of Vietnam.  The extension is Vietnam Vet. The next level is warrior.  I was a &quot;gunbunny&quot;. Battalion Radio Repairman. Not a &quot;grunt, brush buster, lrrp, Ranger, Green Beret.&quot;  I salute those in the bush.  But I feel I am no less a warrior . I have a DD-214 that states I served in Viet Nam.  When asked I tell what I did in-country, with pride.  The hardest thing that I had to understand about my service in country was that is was valuable. That it meant something. My PTSD was not from Vietnam but what happened after.  My six years of counseling centered on why I did two tours and that there was value in giving up my innosence.  So this is a start.<br><br>
Cook, I find it enlightening.  Your stories share things that I have never heard of before. They are thought provoking.  They provide an insight to what combat, the fear,the pain, the loss of senses, the strange and the wonderful.  Knowledge comes in many forms and I'm beginning to see.
